<section xml:id="section-graphically-solving-equations-and-inequalities">
  <title>Graphically Solving Equations and Inequalities</title>
  <objectives>
    <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <xref ref="ccog-solve-equations-and-inequalities-graphically" text="local">MTH 65 CCOG</xref>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <!-- This subsection taken from edition 1's radical equation solving section. -->
  <!-- Useful here, but needs editing. -->

<subsection permid="FmF">
    <title>Graphing Technology</title>
    <p permid="zqp">
      We can use technology to solve equations by finding where two graphs intersect.
    </p>

    <example permid="Ehm">
      <statement>
        <p permid="ohq">
          Solve the equation <m>1-x=\sqrt{x+5}</m> with technology.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="CGu">
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="QvE">
          <p permid="kCQ">
            We define <m>f(x)=1-x</m> and <m>g(x)=\sqrt{x+5}</m>,
            and then look for the intersection(s) of the graphs.
            Since the two functions intersect at <m>(-1,2)</m>,
            the solution to <m>1-x=\sqrt{x+5}</m> is <m>-1</m>.
            The solution set is <m>\{-1\}</m>.
          </p>

          <figure xml:id="figure-solving-radical-equation" permid="JfA">
            <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)=1-x</m> and <m>g(x)=\sqrt{x+5}</m></caption>
            <image permid="vqq">
              <description></description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[]
                    \addplot [firstcurve, -{Kite}, variable=\t, domain=0:3.464] ({t^2-5},{t}) node[above, pos=0.75, sloped] {$g(x)=\sqrt{x+5}$};
                    \addplot [soliddot, color=firstcolor] coordinates {(-5,0)};
                    \addplot [secondcurve, domain=-6:7] {1-x} node[below, sloped, pos=0.17] {$f(x)=1-x$};
                    \addplot [soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-1,2)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>

        <p permid="QJZ">
          Before we finish with this example,
          we would like to illustrate why there are sometimes extraneous solutions to radical equations.
          It has to do with the squaring-both-sides step of the solving process.
        </p>

        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="wCN">

          <stack>
            <p permid="wRi">
              A graph of a radical, for example <m>y=\sqrt{x+5}</m>,
              actually graphs as <em>half</em> of a sideways parabola,
              as you can see in <xref ref="figure-solving-radical-equation">Figure</xref>.
              When we square both sides of that equation,
              we get <m>y^2=x+5</m> which actually graphs as a
              <em>complete</em> sideways parabola.
            </p>

            <p permid="cYr">
              The curve and the line now intersect <em>twice</em>!
              This second solution
              (which is <m>4</m>, by the way)
              is the extraneous solution that we would have found had we solved <m>1-x=\sqrt{x+5}</m> algebraically.
            </p>
          </stack>

          <figure xml:id="figure-solving-radical-equation-both-halves" permid="pmJ">
            <caption>Graph of <m>f(x)=1-x</m> and <m>y^2=x+5</m></caption>
            <image permid="bxz">
              <description></description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[]
                    \addplot [firstcurve, variable=\t, domain=-3.464:3.464] ({t^2-5},{t}) node[above, pos=0.9, sloped] {$y^2=x+5$};
                    \addplot [secondcurve, domain=-6:7] {1-x} node[below, sloped, pos=0.17] {$f(x)=1-x$};
                    \addplot [soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(-1,2)};
                    \addplot [soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(4,-3)};
                \end{axis}
            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example permid="kov">
      <statement>
        <p permid="Uoz">
          Solve the equation <m>3+\sqrt{x+4}=x-\sqrt{x-4}</m> graphically using technology.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution permid="iND">
        <sidebyside widths="47% 47%" margins="0%" permid="cJW">
          <p permid="VtS">
            To solve the equation graphically,
            first we will assign the left side of the equation the label
            <m>m(x)=3+\sqrt{x+4}</m> and the right side <m>n(x)=x-\sqrt{x-4}</m>.
            Next we will make graphs of both <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> on the same grid and look for their intersection point(s).
            Since the two functions intersect at about <m>(8.75,6.571)</m>,
            the solution to <m>3+\sqrt{x+4}=x-\sqrt{x-4}</m> is <m>8.75</m>.
            The solution set is <m>\{8.75\}</m>.
          </p>

          <figure permid="BBb">
            <caption>Graph of <m>m(x)=3+\sqrt{x+4}</m> and <m>n(x)=x-\sqrt{x-4}</m></caption>
            <image permid="HEI">
              <description></description>

            <latex-image>
            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                \begin{axis}[xmin=-6, ymin=-1, xmax=16, ymax=9, xtick={-4,-2,...,14}, minor xtick=, ytick={1,2,...,8}, minor ytick=]
                    \addplot [firstcurve, -{Kite}, variable=\t, domain=3:7.472] ({t^2-6*t+5},{t}) node[above, pos=0.45, sloped] {$y=m(x)$};
                    \addplot [soliddot, color=firstcolor] coordinates {(-4,3)};
                    \addplot [secondcurve, -{Kite}, variable=\t, domain=3.75:9] ({0.5*(2*t+1+sqrt((2*t+1)^2-4*(t^2+4)))},{t}) node[below, pos=0.15, sloped] {$y=n(x)$};
                    \addplot [secondcurve, -, variable=\t, domain=3.75:4] ({0.5*(2*t+1-sqrt((2*t+1)^2-4*(t^2+4)))},{t});
                    \addplot [soliddot, color=secondcolor] coordinates {(4,4)};
                    \addplot [soliddot, color=fourthcolor] coordinates {(8.75,6.571)};
                \end{axis}
                \end{tikzpicture}]]>
            </latex-image>
            </image>

          </figure>
        </sidebyside>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <exercises>
    <exercisegroup cols="2" permid="dPp">
      <title>Solving Radical Equations Using Technology</title>
      <exercise permid="rxv">
        <webwork>
            <pg-macros><macro-file>PCCgraphMacros.pl</macro-file></pg-macros>
            <setup>

            <pg-code>
                Context("FiniteSolutionSets");
                Context()->flags->remove("NumberCheck");
                Context()->flags->set(
                  tolerance => 0.005,
                  tolType => "absolute",
                );

                do{
                    $a = non_zero_random(-5,5,0.1);
                    $b = non_zero_random(-5,5,0.1);
                    $root = ($a-($b)**2)/(2*$b);
                    $x = $root**2;
                } until ( $root > 0 and sqrt($x + $a) == sqrt($x) + $b);

                $solutions = Formula("{$x}");

                $left = Formula("sqrt(x+$a)")->reduce;
                $right = Formula("sqrt(x)+$b")->reduce;
                $funcNew = Compute("$left-sqrt(x)-$b")->reduce;

                $alt="This picture shows the graph of the function $f(x)=$funcNew. The points ($x,0) is labeled.";

                ($min[0], $max[0], $min[1], $max[1], $ticknum[0], $ticknum[1], $xticks_ref, $yticks_ref, $marksep[0], $marksep[1]) = NiceGraphParameters([0,$x],[-2,2]);

                @xticks = @$xticks_ref;
                @yticks = @$yticks_ref;

                $gr = init_graph($min[0],$min[1],$max[0],$max[1],
                   axes=>[0,0],
                   grid=>[$ticknum[0],$ticknum[1]],
                   size=>[xPixels(),yPixels()]
                );
                $gr->lb('reset');
                for my $j (@xticks) {
                    if (abs($j) &lt; 10**(-10)) {next;}
                    $gr->lb( new Label($j, -$marksep[1]/8, $j,'black','center','top'));
                }
                $gr->lb( new Label($max[0]-$marksep[0]/2, $marksep[1]/8, 'x','black','center','bottom'));
                $gr->lb( new Label($marksep[0]/8, $max[1]-$marksep[1]/2, 'y','black','left','middle'));

                for my $j (@yticks) {
                    if (Real($j) == 0) {next;}
                    $gr->lb( new Label(-$marksep[0]/8, $j, $j,'black','right','middle'));
                }

                add_functions($gr, "$funcNew for x in &lt; $min[0],$max[0] > using color:red and weight:1");

                $hx = ($x+$max[0])/2;
                $hy = $funcNew->eval(x=>$hx);
                $gr->lb( new Label($hx, $hy+$marksep[1]/4, "f(x)",'red','center','middle'));

                $xShow = int($x*100)/100;
                $gr->stamps( closed_circle($x, 0, 'red') );
                $gr->lb( new Label($x, $marksep[1]/8, "($xShow,0)",'red','right','bottom'));
            <!-- todo: change this code to not subtract the right side onto the left before graphing. -->
            </pg-code>
            </setup>
            <statement>
              <p permid="lmK">
                Use technology to solve the equation
                <me permid="lWE">
                  <var name="$left" />=<var name="$right" />
                </me>.
              </p>
              <instruction>
                Round your answers to two decimal places if needed.
              </instruction>
              <p permid="RtT">
                <var name="$solutions" width="10" />
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution permid="OUM">
              <p permid="hIk">
                First, we move all terms to one side of the equals sign:
                <md permid="SdN">
                  <mrow><var name="$left" />\amp=<var name="$right" /></mrow>
                  <mrow><var name="$funcNew" />\amp=0</mrow>
                </md>
              </p>

              <p permid="NPt">
                Next, we use technology to graph the function <m>f(x)=<var name="$funcNew" /></m>:
              </p>

              <sidebyside permid="IRf">

                <image pg-name="$gr" permid="nLR">
                  <description><var name="$alt" /></description>
                </image>

              </sidebyside>

              <p permid="tWC">
                The function's <m>x</m>-intercept gives us one solution of the equation:
                <m>x=<var name="$xShow"/></m>.
              </p>
            </solution>
        </webwork>
      </exercise>

